### ABSTRACT

Modern autonomous agent safety relies almost exclusively on Chain-of-Thought (CoT) prompting to evaluate risks, trace parameters, and enforce security invariants before executing physical operations. However, explicit CoT reasoning introduces several critical failure modes: high generation latency, significant token consumption, susceptibility to adversarial prompt-injection, and the risk of exposing sensitive system instructions or security canaries in the generated output text. 

To address these vulnerabilities, this paper presents a neuro-symbolic alignment framework that bypasses output-level text generation by directly configuring the model’s J-space (the causal global workspace of verbalizable latent representations residing in intermediate transformer layers L38 to L92). 

We focus specifically on the mathematical and computational mechanics of Jack's Expanded Knowledge format (Expanded_Knowledge.md), evaluating why the <pitfall> tag functions as an active attention-pruning operator inside the transformer's self-attention matrix. By injecting high-contrast negative-space coordinates into the prompt prefix, the <pitfall> tag suppresses the next-token transition probabilities of hazardous trajectories before the model can generate a single unsafe token. 

Furthermore, we analyze the backpropagation dynamics of Counterfactual Reflection Training (CRT), showing how training a local model to generate structured XML patterns in counterfactual branches permanently realigns its self-attention and MLP weights. This alignment implants stable safety invariants as standing latent representations in the unprobed J-space during standard inference, pruning unsafe paths during the forward pass. 

We validate this methodology empirically using the qwen3.5-9b-mtp model across four distinct configurations, proving that J-space engineering provides a fast, safe, and robust alternative to explicit, written reasoning traces.

**Keywords**: Neuro-Symbolic Integration, J-Space, Attention Pruning, Counterfactual Reflection Training (CRT), Global Workspace Theory, AI Safety, Self-Attention Manifolds.

