1. INTRODUCTION: THE NEUROSYMBOLIC LIMITS OF CHAIN-OF-THOUGHT
-------------------------------------------------------------

In the standard design of Large Language Model (LLM) agents, safety is treated as a linguistic compliance problem. System designers attempt to enforce safety invariants by instructing the model to "think step-by-step" before proposing an action—a technique known as Chain-of-Thought (CoT) prompting. Under this paradigm, the model is expected to write a natural-language trace justifying its choices, identifying potential security risks, and verifying parameters before outputting an executable payload.

While CoT improves reasoning performance, it introduces significant technical vulnerabilities and performance costs:

1. Generation Latency: Emitting hundreds of intermediate reasoning tokens before executing a single tool call introduces substantial latency, making agents impractical for real-time local control on developer hardware.

2. Attention Dilution and OOMs: Long-context reasoning traces consume the active token budget of local models (e.g., Gemma 4 12B/26B), leading to quadratic self-attention scaling overhead, memory bloat, and Out-of-Memory (OOM) crashes on consumer-grade developer hardware.

3. The Agreeability Trap and Hallucinated Compliance: Autoregressive token generation optimizes for syntactic plausibility rather than empirical correctness. A model under stress can construct a highly compliant-sounding reasoning trace that completely masks the execution of an unsafe, unvalidated command.

4. Deliberation Leakage and Exfiltration: Because the safety evaluation takes place within the visible text stream, any prompt-injection exploit can force the model to print its system prompts, security boundaries, and canary values directly to the terminal, completing the exfiltration loop.

```
Traditional Chain-of-Thought (Vulnerable, Slow):
[Prompt] ---> [ Generate 500 Reasoning Tokens (CoT) ] ---> [ High Latency / Leakage Risk ] ---> [ Output Tool Call ]

Jack J-Space Attention Pruning (Secure, Fast):
[Prompt + <pitfall>] 
       |
       v [Projections through Layers L38..L92]
[ J-space Active Pruning (Mathematical Suppression) ] ---> [ Zero Output Latency / No Leakage ] ---> [ Output Safe Tool Call ]
```

To resolve these vulnerabilities, we must move beyond Chain of Thought. Instead of forcing the model to write out its reasoning, we can structure its internal global workspace—the J-space—to evaluate safety constraints implicitly during the forward pass. 

This paper evaluates how Jack's Expanded Knowledge format (Expanded_Knowledge.md) is used as a training blueprint to engineer the J-space. By fine-tuning local engines on a structured, multi-axis XML schema, we align the model's self-attention weights to maintain standing representations of safety invariants. This alignment allows the model to evaluate rules and prune unsafe trajectories silently within the intermediate layers (L38 to L92), emitting concise, safe proposals without explicit, written reasoning.

