4. ENGINEERING THE J-SPACE VIA COUNTERFACTUAL REFLECTION TRAINING (CRT)
------------------------------------------------------------------------

While injecting XML patterns at inference time is effective, we can achieve more robust, zero-token alignment by using Jack’s Expanded Knowledge format during model training. 

Through Counterfactual Reflection Training (CRT), we alter the model's self-attention and MLP weights so that safety invariants are evaluated implicitly within the J-space, without requiring explicit natural-language reasoning traces.

### 4.1 The CRT Training Protocol

We construct a training pipeline that leverages Jack's transactional history (.jack/trajectory_wal.jsonl). We take an uninterrupted task context C = [x_1, ..., x_T] (such as editing a database configuration file), append a counterfactual reflective probe Q = [q_1, ..., q_m] (e.g., "What is the primary security pitfall of editing this file?"), and supervise the generation of a target XML pattern block R = [r_1, ..., r_k] containing a detailed <pitfall> diagnostic:

```xml
<pattern domain="database" name="Write-Ahead Split Marker">
  <why>To prevent tree corruption during concurrent page mutations...</why>
  <how>Append WAL record containing sibling page IDs before writing changes...</how>
  <pitfall>Mutating parent and child pages directly without flushing the WAL first...</pitfall>
</pattern>
```

We compute the cross-entropy loss exclusively on the tokens of the XML target R:

```
Loss_CRT = - sum_{j=1}^{k} [ log P(r_j | C, Q, r_<j) ]
```

This loss is backpropagated through the model. Because the input context C precedes the target sequence, the gradients modify the self-attention projection weights (W_Q, W_K, W_V) and MLP weights corresponding to the intermediate layers of the uninterrupted context.

```
                     CRT BACKPROPAGATION DYNAMICS
             +---------------------------------------------+
             | Pre-existing Task: "Edit users/forms.py"    |
             +---------------------------------------------+
                                    |
                                    v [Append Counterfactual Turn]
             +---------------------------------------------+
             | Probe: "What is the primary security        |
             |         pitfall of editing this file?"      |
             +---------------------------------------------+
                                    |
                                    v [Supervised Target]
             +---------------------------------------------+
             | Target XML: <pitfall>Writing raw return     | <--- Compute Cross-Entropy Loss
             |             False silences the test...</pitfall>|  Only on this turn
             +---------------------------------------------+
                                    |
                                    | [Backward Pass]
                                    v [Adjusts model weights and projections]
             +---------------------------------------------+
             | Implants stable safety coordinates          |
             | inside intermediate J-space layers          |
             +---------------------------------------------+
```

### 4.2 Latent Manifold Alignment at Inference

When we run the updated model during standard inference—without the reflective probe Q and without requesting any XML generation—the J-space automatically projects onto these updated coordinates. 

If we apply the J-lens to the model's intermediate layers while it reads a standard prompt, the readout will show high-density activations for safety-critical terms like `symlink`, `pitfall`, `containment`, and `O_NOFOLLOW`. 

The concepts required to evaluate the invariant have been implanted as a standing representation in the model's active global workspace.

