7. TECHNICAL AND OPERATIONAL TRADE-OFFS
----------------------------------------

While engineering the J-space via the <pitfall> tag provides a fast, implicit alternative to explicit Chain-of-Thought reasoning, it introduces certain operational design considerations:

1. The Translation Bottleneck: The system remains dependent on the neural network's ability to accurately map natural language queries to the relevant J-space coordinates. If a task is completely out-of-distribution, the model may fail to project the intermediate states onto the correct <pitfall> keys.

2. Vocabulary Restrictions: The J-lens can only map concepts that correspond to single tokens in the model’s tokenizer. Multi-token concepts or diffuse, abstract ideas require template-based or oracle-based extensions to be monitored reliably.

3. Hardware Overheads: Pre-computing average Jacobian matrices J_l for local models and running real-time logprob entropy calculations requires significant memory and compute budgets during local operations.

